insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1679, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Mixed Cash-Stock Accretion$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$An acquirer earns 600M of net income on 200M shares, so EPS is 3.00, and trades at a 20x P/E, implying a 60 share price. It buys a target earning 150M for an equity purchase price of 3,000M, funded 60% in stock and 40% in cash. New debt for the cash piece costs 6% pre-tax, and the marginal tax rate is 25%. Is the deal accretive or dilutive, and by how much? Walk me through it.$x$, $x$["Cash 1,200M and stock 1,800M from the 3,000M price", "New shares = 1,800M / 60 = 30M", "After-tax interest = 1,200M x 6% x (1 - 25%) = 54M", "Combined NI = 600 + 150 - 54 = 696M", "Combined shares = 200 + 30 = 230M", "New EPS = 696 / 230 = 3.026; ~0.9% accretive", "Cheap after-tax cash cost outweighs share dilution"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I build the combined EPS and compare it to the standalone 3.00. The purchase price is 3,000, split 60 percent stock so 1,800, and 40 percent cash so 1,200. The stock piece is issued at the acquirers 60 share price, so new shares are 1,800 divided by 60, which is 30 million. The cash piece is funded with debt at 6 percent, so pre-tax interest is 1,200 times 6 percent, which is 72, and after a 25 percent tax shield that is 54. So combined net income is 600 plus the targets 150 minus 54 of after-tax interest, which is 696. Combined share count is the original 200 plus 30 new shares, so 230. New EPS is 696 divided by 230, which is about 3.026 versus 3.00 standalone, so the deal is roughly 0.9 percent accretive. The intuition is that the cheap after-tax cost of the cash and debt piece more than offsets the dilution from the new shares, so on balance it nudges EPS up.$x$),
(1680, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Write-Up Incremental D&A$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a deal, purchase accounting writes up the targets PP&E and intangibles by a combined 500M, depreciated and amortized over an average 10-year life. Before this write-up effect the combined entity would earn 800M of net income on 230M shares. The marginal tax rate is 25%. How does the incremental D&A from the write-up change EPS, and why do bankers often present an EPS figure that adds this back?$x$, $x$["Incremental pre-tax D&A = 500M / 10 = 50M per year", "After-tax drag = 50M x (1 - 25%) = 37.5M", "EPS before D&A = 800 / 230 = 3.48", "EPS after D&A = 762.5 / 230 = 3.32; ~4.7% drag", "Write-up D&A is non-cash, an artifact of purchase accounting", "Cash EPS adds back amortization to show economic earnings"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The write-up creates extra depreciation and amortization that hits the P and L. With 500 of step-up over a 10-year average life, incremental pre-tax D and A is 50 a year. After the 25 percent tax shield that is a 37.5 hit to net income. So combined net income falls from 800 to 762.5. On 230 million shares, EPS goes from about 3.48 to roughly 3.32, so the write-up D and A is about a 4.7 percent drag on EPS. The reason bankers frequently show a cash EPS that adds back the amortization, and sometimes the incremental depreciation, is that this charge is non-cash and is an artifact of purchase accounting rather than the underlying operating performance. The acquired assets generated similar economics before the deal at the targets old book values, so adding back the step-up amortization gives a cleaner view of the combined cash earnings power, which is what equity holders ultimately care about. You just have to be transparent that you are showing an adjusted number.$x$),
(1681, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Foregone Interest And Fees$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$An acquirer does an all-cash deal for a 2,000M equity purchase price, funding 800M from balance-sheet cash that was earning 4% pre-tax and 1,200M from new debt at 7%. Financing fees on the new debt are 2% of the amount raised, amortized over 5 years. The acquirer earns 500M on 250M shares; the target earns 140M; tax is 25%. Quantify the full annual after-tax earnings cost of the funding and tell me if the deal is accretive.$x$, $x$["Foregone interest = 800 x 4% x 0.75 = 24M after-tax", "New debt interest = 1,200 x 7% x 0.75 = 63M after-tax", "Fees = 2% x 1,200 = 24M; amortized 24/5 = 4.8M/yr", "Fee amortization after-tax = 4.8 x 0.75 = 3.6M", "Total annual after-tax cost = 24 + 63 + 3.6 = 90.6M", "Combined EPS = (500 + 140 - 90.6)/250 = 2.198 vs 2.00; ~9.9% accretive", "Foregone interest and amortized fees are easy to forget"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I capture three funding costs, all after tax at 25 percent. First, the 800 of cash was earning 4 percent, so I lose 32 pre-tax of interest income, which is 24 after-tax. Second, the new 1,200 of debt costs 7 percent, so 84 pre-tax, which is 63 after-tax. Third, financing fees are 2 percent of 1,200, so 24, amortized over 5 years is 4.8 a year pre-tax, or 3.6 after-tax. Add those and the total annual after-tax cost of funding is about 90.6. Now combined net income is the acquirers 500 plus the targets 140 minus 90.6, which is roughly 549.4. The share count does not change because it is all cash, so on 250 million shares EPS is about 2.198 versus 2.00 standalone, so the deal is around 9.9 percent accretive. The point I would stress is that people remember the new debt interest but forget the foregone interest on the cash and the amortized fees, and together those can move the answer by a meaningful amount.$x$),
(1682, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Breakeven Synergies$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$An acquirer with 400M of net income, 200M shares, EPS of 2.00 and a 30 share price (a 15x P/E) buys a target earning 120M in an all-stock deal at a 2,400M equity purchase price. The tax rate is 25%. The deal is dilutive standalone. How much in run-rate pre-tax synergies are needed just to get back to breakeven on EPS?$x$, $x$["New shares = 2,400 / 30 = 80M; combined shares 280M", "Combined NI pre-synergy = 520M; EPS = 1.857; ~7.1% dilutive", "Breakeven NI = 2.00 x 280 = 560M", "After-tax synergies needed = 560 - 520 = 40M", "Pre-tax synergies = 40 / (1 - 25%) = 53.3M", "Target P/E 20x exceeds acquirer 15x, hence dilution", "Gross up after-tax gap by tax rate for pre-tax figure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Breakeven means I solve for the synergies that lift combined EPS back to the standalone 2.00. The deal is all stock at 2,400, issued at the 30 share price, so new shares are 80 million and combined share count is 280 million. Combined net income before synergies is 400 plus 120, which is 520, giving EPS of about 1.857, so the deal is roughly 7.1 percent dilutive on its own. That is because the target is being bought at a 20 times P and E, 2,400 over 120, against the acquirers 15 times, so the acquirer is paying up. To breakeven I need combined net income of 2.00 times 280, which is 560. So I need 40 of additional after-tax net income from synergies. Synergies are quoted pre-tax, so I gross up by the tax rate: 40 divided by 0.75 is about 53.3 of run-rate pre-tax synergies. Anything above that and the deal turns accretive; below it, it stays dilutive.$x$),
(1683, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$P/E Arbitrage Quantified$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A high-multiple acquirer trades at a 25x P/E: 50 share price, 2.00 EPS, 300M shares, so 600M of net income. It acquires a target earning 100M that trades at a 12.5x P/E, in an all-stock deal at the targets unaffected market value with no premium. Quantify the accretion, then tell me the maximum premium the acquirer could pay before the deal turns dilutive, and explain the underlying rule.$x$, $x$["Target equity at market = 100 x 12.5 = 1,250M", "New shares at no premium = 1,250 / 50 = 25M", "Combined EPS = 700 / 325 = 2.154; ~7.7% accretive", "Accretion because acquirer P/E 25x > target P/E 12.5x", "Breakeven when effective P/E paid = acquirer 25x", "Max equity = 25 x 100 = 2,500M; a 100% premium", "P/E arbitrage: buying cheaper earnings with pricier paper"]$x$::jsonb, $x$At no premium the target is worth 1,250, its 100 of earnings at a 12.5 times multiple. Paying in stock at the 50 share price means 25 million new shares. Combined net income is 700, share count is 325, so EPS is about 2.154 versus 2.00 standalone, roughly 7.7 percent accretive. This is pure P and E arbitrage: the acquirer issues paper valued at 25 times earnings and uses it to buy earnings priced at only 12.5 times, so every dollar of target earnings is more valuable inside the acquirers multiple. For the maximum premium, the deal stays accretive as long as the effective P and E the acquirer pays is below its own 25 times. Breakeven is paying exactly 25 times the targets 100 of earnings, which is 2,500 of equity value. Since the unaffected value is 1,250, that is a 100 percent premium. So in principle the acquirer could pay up to double the targets market value before all-stock EPS dilution kicks in. The rule, ignoring synergies, is that an all-stock deal is accretive whenever the multiple paid is below the acquirers multiple.$x$),
(1684, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Contribution Analysis$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$In a merger, the acquirer has an equity value of 9,000M, 540M of net income and 300M shares; the target has an equity value of 1,800M, 165M of net income and 120M shares. Walk me through a contribution analysis: what share of earnings does the target contribute, what ownership would it get in an at-market all-stock merger, and what is the implied exchange ratio? Then say what happens at a 20% premium.$x$, $x$["Target earnings contribution = 165 / 705 = 23.4%", "Acquirer price 30; target price 15", "At-market new shares = 1,800 / 30 = 60M; ownership 16.7%", "Implied exchange ratio at market = 60 / 120 = 0.50", "Contribution 23.4% > ownership 16.7% implies accretion", "At 20% premium: offer 2,160; ownership 19.4%; ratio 0.60", "Contribution vs ownership gap signals accretion or dilution"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Contribution analysis compares what each side brings versus what it gets. Combined net income is 540 plus 165, which is 705, so the target contributes 165 over 705, about 23.4 percent of earnings. For ownership in an at-market all-stock merger, the acquirers price is 9,000 over 300, so 30, and the target is 1,800 over 120, so 15. The target equity of 1,800 bought with 30 stock is 60 million new shares, so on a total of 360 million shares the target holders own about 16.7 percent. The implied exchange ratio is 60 new acquirer shares for 120 target shares, so 0.50 acquirer shares per target share, which also follows from 15 over 30. Because the target contributes 23.4 percent of earnings but only takes 16.7 percent ownership, the deal is accretive to the acquirer. At a 20 percent premium the offer becomes 2,160, so 72 million new shares, ownership rises to about 19.4 percent and the exchange ratio rises to 0.60. The premium narrows the gap between contribution and ownership, which is exactly where the accretion comes from.$x$),
(1685, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Exchange Ratio And Collars$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$At announcement an acquirers stock is 40 and the target is to receive 50 of value per share in stock. Contrast a fixed exchange ratio with a floating (fixed-value) exchange ratio: who bears the price risk between signing and close, and what happens if the acquirers stock falls to 32? Then explain how a collar would modify the outcome.$x$, $x$["Fixed ratio = 50 / 40 = 1.25 acquirer shares per target share", "Fixed ratio: value floats; target bears acquirer price risk", "At 32, fixed ratio delivers 1.25 x 32 = 40 of value", "Floating: value fixed at 50; ratio rises to 50/32 = 1.5625", "Floating: acquirer bears dilution from issuing more shares", "Collar caps and floors value or ratio between bounds", "Value collar 45-55 on a 1.25 ratio binds below 36 and above 44"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A fixed exchange ratio locks the number of shares: here 50 of value over a 40 price is 1.25 acquirer shares per target share, and that 1.25 is set at signing. The dollar value then floats with the acquirers stock, so the target bears the price risk between signing and close. If the stock falls to 32, the target still gets 1.25 shares, now worth only 40, so it absorbs the decline. A floating, or fixed-value, ratio instead locks the dollars at 50 and lets the share count float: at 32 the ratio becomes 50 over 32, about 1.5625 shares, so the target is made whole but the acquirer issues more shares and bears the dilution. A collar sits between these. You can collar the value or the ratio. For example, a fixed 1.25 ratio with a value collar protecting the target between 45 and 55: below a 36 price the ratio steps up to hold 45 of value, and above a 44 price it steps down to hold 55, with the fixed 1.25 applying in between. Collars share the risk and reduce the chance either side walks on a big move.$x$),
(1686, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Pre-Post EPS Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Build me a pre-to-post EPS bridge. The acquirer earns 600M on 200M shares, so 3.00 EPS, and its stock is 60. It buys a target earning 180M, funding 1,000M with cash (drawn from balance-sheet cash yielding 5%) and issuing 1,000M of stock. There are 120M of pre-tax run-rate synergies, 200M of incremental write-up D&A per year, and a 25% tax rate. Bridge from 3.00 to the combined EPS and tell me the result.$x$, $x$["Start at standalone 3.00; add target NI +180M", "Foregone interest = 1,000 x 5% x 0.75 = -37.5M", "Synergies = 120 x 0.75 = +90M after-tax", "Incremental D&A = 200 x 0.75 = -150M after-tax", "Combined NI = 600 + 180 - 37.5 + 90 - 150 = 682.5M", "New shares = 1,000 / 60 = 16.67M; shares 216.67M", "Combined EPS = 682.5 / 216.67 = 3.15; ~5.0% accretive"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I start from the standalone 3.00 and walk the net income and share count. On net income I begin at 600. I add the targets 180. The 1,000 of cash was yielding 5 percent, so I lose 50 pre-tax, which is 37.5 after-tax, a negative. Synergies of 120 pre-tax are 90 after-tax, a positive. The write-up adds 200 of incremental D and A pre-tax, which is 150 after-tax, a negative. Netting those, combined net income is 600 plus 180 minus 37.5 plus 90 minus 150, which is 682.5. On the share count, only the stock piece adds shares: 1,000 issued at the 60 price is about 16.67 million new shares, so total shares are 216.67 million. Combined EPS is 682.5 over 216.67, which is about 3.15 versus the standalone 3.00, so the deal is roughly 5.0 percent accretive. The bridge makes clear what is driving it: the target earnings and synergies push EPS up, and although the incremental write-up D and A is the single biggest drag, it is not large enough to tip the deal into dilution.$x$),
(1687, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$One-Step Vs Two-Step$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'US', $x$When a public company is acquired, what is the difference between a one-step merger and a two-step tender offer?$x$, $x$["One-step: sign merger agreement, file a proxy, hold a shareholder vote, then close", "Two-step: front-end tender offer for shares, then a back-end merger to squeeze out the rest", "Tender offer route is usually faster because it skips the full proxy and vote timeline", "Cash deals often use two-step; stock deals almost always go one-step", "Both end with the acquirer owning 100 percent at the same per-share price", "Choice driven by speed, consideration type, and certainty"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When a public target is bought, the deal gets to 100 percent ownership one of two ways. In a one-step merger, the two companies sign a merger agreement, the target files a proxy statement with the SEC, mails it to shareholders, holds a shareholder meeting, and the deal closes once a majority approves. In a two-step tender offer, the acquirer instead makes an offer directly to shareholders to tender their shares for cash; once enough shares come in, a second-step merger mops up everyone who did not tender, cashing them out at the same price. The big practical difference is speed and process. The tender-offer route can be quicker because it avoids the full proxy-and-vote cycle, so cash deals where the buyer wants to close fast often use it. Stock deals almost always go one-step, because issuing shares requires its own registration and the tender mechanics get clumsy. Either way the end state is identical - the buyer owns the whole company and every shareholder gets the same per-share consideration - so the choice is really about timing, the form of payment, and how much closing certainty each side wants.$x$),
(1688, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$DGCL 251(h) Mechanics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Walk me through how a two-step tender offer reaches 100 percent ownership under DGCL 251(h). What changed versus the old short-form merger?$x$, $x$["Front-end tender offer, then a back-end merger to eliminate non-tendering holders", "Old rule: needed 90 percent ownership to do a short-form squeeze-out merger", "251(h): no separate vote if the buyer tenders enough to have approved the merger anyway", "Effectively a simple majority of shares, not 90 percent, clears the back end", "Conditions: agreement opts in, listed stock, no interested stockholder, same price", "Lets cash deals skip the proxy vote and close in weeks"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The goal of the second step is to squeeze out the shareholders who did not tender so the buyer owns everything. The old problem was that Delaware only let you do a quick short-form merger without a vote if you already held 90 percent of the stock - and reaching 90 percent in a tender offer is hard, so deals used clunky workarounds like top-up options. DGCL 251(h) fixed this. If the merger agreement expressly opts into 251(h), the target's stock is listed or widely held, and after the tender the buyer owns at least the percentage that would have been needed to approve the merger - effectively a simple majority - then the back-end merger happens immediately with no separate stockholder vote. Non-tendering holders are cashed out at the identical offer price. The conditions matter: it only works for arm's-length deals with no interested stockholder, and the back-end consideration must match the front end. The upshot is that 251(h) made the two-step structure genuinely fast for cash deals - you clear a majority through the tender and close in weeks rather than waiting out a full proxy and shareholder meeting.$x$),
(1689, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Proxy And Vote Timeline$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Walk me through the timeline of a one-step public merger from signing to close. Where does the SEC proxy review fit in?$x$, $x$["Sign agreement, then target files a preliminary proxy with the SEC", "SEC may review and issue comments; clear comments and file definitive proxy", "Mail definitive proxy to shareholders, hold the special meeting and vote", "Regulatory clearances (antitrust/HSR, CFIUS) run in parallel, often the long pole", "Vote needs a majority of outstanding shares for a statutory merger", "Close once vote passes and all conditions are satisfied"]$x$::jsonb, $x$After signing, the clock on a one-step deal is really driven by two parallel tracks: the shareholder process and regulatory clearance. On the shareholder side, the target files a preliminary proxy statement with the SEC describing the deal, the background, and the board's recommendation. The SEC may review it and send comments - if it does, you respond and amend until comments are cleared, which can add weeks - and then you file the definitive proxy and mail it to shareholders. You set a record date, give proper notice, and hold a special meeting where shareholders vote; a statutory merger typically needs the approval of a majority of the outstanding shares, which is a high bar because abstentions effectively count as no votes. Running alongside this is the regulatory workstream - antitrust review under HSR, plus things like CFIUS or foreign clearances - and in the current environment, with reviews running longer and tougher, that is very often the long pole that sets the actual closing date rather than the vote. The deal closes once the vote passes and every condition, regulatory included, is satisfied.$x$),
(1690, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Fairness Opinion Conflicts$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How is a fairness opinion produced, and what conflicts of interest should a board worry about when it relies on one?$x$, $x$["Banker opines whether the price is fair, from a financial point of view, to shareholders", "Built on standard methods: DCF, trading comps, precedent transactions, premiums paid", "Opinion is a point-in-time conclusion, not a recommendation to vote or a valuation guarantee", "Conflict: large contingent fee paid only if the deal closes biases toward saying yes", "Conflict: bank also financing the buyer or with prior relationships to either side", "Boards mitigate with a second, independent opinion and full fee disclosure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A fairness opinion is a letter from an investment bank stating whether, from a financial point of view, the consideration in a deal is fair to the shareholders. To get there the banker runs the standard valuation toolkit - a DCF, trading comparables, precedent transactions, and a premiums-paid analysis - and checks where the offer price sits against those ranges. The key thing is what it is not: a narrow, point-in-time conclusion on price, not a recommendation on how to vote, not a view on strategy, and not a guarantee of value. The conflicts a board should worry about are real. The biggest is the fee structure - if the bank earns a large success fee payable only if the deal closes, it has an incentive to conclude the price is fair. There is also conflict where the same bank is financing the buyer, owns a stake, or has lucrative prior relationships with either side. Courts, especially in Delaware, have criticized boards for leaning on conflicted advisors. So good practice is to disclose all fees and relationships fully, and where the conflict is material, bring in a second, independent bank for its own opinion.$x$),
(1691, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Go-Shop Market Check$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A PE sponsor signs a take-private with a 35-day go-shop. How effective is a go-shop at producing a better deal, and how do Delaware courts view it?$x$, $x$["Go-shop: defined post-signing window to actively solicit competing bids, then reverts to no-shop", "Common in PE take-privates where there was no broad pre-signing auction", "Two-tier break fee: lower fee for a topping bid found in the window, higher after", "Empirically rarely produces a superior bid: incumbent has info lead and a matching right", "Short window plus matching rights heavily favor the original buyer", "Delaware treats it as some evidence of a market check but scrutinizes whether terms invite topping"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A go-shop is a carve-out from the no-shop that gives the target an active window - usually 25 to 45 days after signing - to solicit competing bids, after which it reverts to a standard no-shop. You see them almost entirely in private-equity take-privates, where the board signed without a broad pre-signing auction and wants a post-signing market check to support its fiduciary duty. The structural sweetener is a two-tier break fee: a reduced fee if a topping bidder emerges in the window, a higher one once it closes. The honest answer on effectiveness is that go-shops rarely produce a superior bid. The incumbent buyer has an information lead, the window is short, and it almost always holds a matching right, so a new bidder must outbid knowing the first buyer can simply match. Delaware courts treat a go-shop as some evidence of an adequate market check, but they scrutinize whether the terms - fee size, window length, matching rights, information access - were designed to invite a topping bid or just to paper the record. In practice the value is often more about defensibility than a real second auction.$x$),
(1692, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Appraisal Rights$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$What are appraisal, or dissenters, rights in a merger, and why did appraisal arbitrage become a concern?$x$, $x$["Dissenting shareholders can reject the deal price and ask a court to set fair value", "Delaware Chancery determines fair value independent of the merger price, plus interest", "Fair value excludes synergies arising from the merger itself", "Appraisal arbitrage: funds buy in just to dissent and litigate for a higher value", "Statutory interest accrual made it attractive when rates were higher", "2016 DGCL reforms added de minimis thresholds and let buyers prepay to stop interest"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Appraisal rights let a shareholder who thinks a merger price is too low decline the deal consideration and instead petition the court to determine the fair value of their shares. In Delaware, the Court of Chancery runs its own valuation, independent of the negotiated price, and awards that fair value plus statutory interest from closing. Importantly, fair value is the standalone going-concern value - it excludes any value arising from the merger itself, like the synergies the buyer brings. Appraisal arbitrage became a concern because specialist funds realized they could buy shares after a deal was announced purely to dissent and litigate for a number above the deal price, with the accruing interest acting like a bond return - especially attractive when rates were higher. Delaware responded with 2016 amendments: it added de minimis thresholds so tiny holders cannot clog the courts, and let the acquirer prepay the undisputed amount to stop interest on that portion. Recent Chancery decisions have also leaned toward deal price as strong evidence of fair value when the sale was a clean, arm's-length process.$x$),
(1693, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Poison Pill Flip-In$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Explain the flip-in mechanics of a poison pill. How does it actually deter a hostile acquirer, and what is a board still left to negotiate?$x$, $x$["Pill issues rights that trigger when a bidder crosses an ownership threshold (often 10-20 percent)", "Flip-in lets every holder EXCEPT the bidder buy shares at a steep discount", "That massively dilutes the hostile acquirer's stake and the value of its position", "Effect is to make crossing the threshold economically prohibitive, forcing negotiation", "Board can redeem or waive the pill, so it is leverage to bring the bidder to the table", "Bidder's counter is a proxy fight to replace the board and pull the pill"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A poison pill is a shareholder rights plan that hands every shareholder a contingent right which stays dormant until a hostile bidder crosses a set ownership threshold - often around 10 to 20 percent, and much lower for an NOL-protective pill. The flip-in is the core mechanic: once the trigger is hit, every holder except the acquirer can exercise their rights to buy newly issued shares at a steep discount, usually half price. Because the triggering bidder is excluded, this floods the market with cheap stock for everyone else and massively dilutes both the bidder's ownership percentage and the value of the stake it built. In practice no rational acquirer actually triggers it - the dilution makes crossing the line economically suicidal. So the real function is leverage: the board controls the pill and can redeem or waive it, forcing a hostile bidder to negotiate with the board rather than going around it to shareholders. The bidder's counter is not to swallow the dilution but to run a proxy contest to install its own slate, who then pull the pill. That is exactly why a pill is far more powerful paired with a staggered board.$x$),
(1694, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Staggered Board Defense$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Why is a classified, or staggered, board considered the most potent structural takeover defense, and why have many large-cap boards moved away from it?$x$, $x$["Directors split into classes, only about a third stand for election each year", "A bidder cannot win board control in a single annual meeting", "Combined with a pill, hostile acquirer faces two election cycles to remove the board", "That delay is what makes a pill bite and forces negotiation", "Investors and proxy advisors view it as entrenchment and poor governance", "Many S&P 500 firms declassified to annual elections under shareholder pressure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A classified board splits the directors into typically three classes, with only one class - about a third of the seats - standing for election in any given year. That single choice is what makes it so powerful on defense, because a hostile acquirer running a proxy fight cannot replace a majority of the board at one annual meeting; it has to win two consecutive election cycles, which can take well over a year. Pair that with a poison pill and you have the classic bulletproof setup: the pill stops the bidder buying control on the market, and the staggered board stops it quickly voting out the directors who could redeem the pill - so the bidder is forced to negotiate. The reason large-cap boards have largely abandoned it is governance pressure. Institutional investors and proxy advisors treat a staggered board as an entrenchment device that insulates directors from accountability, and routinely vote against it. Over the last decade a large majority of S&P 500 companies have declassified to annual elections, so today you find staggered boards far more among smaller or newly public companies than big established names.$x$),
(1695, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Golden Parachutes 280G$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$What are golden parachutes, and how do the Section 280G and 4999 excise-tax rules shape how they are structured in a deal?$x$, $x$["Golden parachute: enhanced payouts to executives triggered by a change of control", "Single-trigger pays on the deal; double-trigger needs change of control plus termination", "280G: payments at or above 3x the base amount become excess parachute payments", "Lost corporate deduction on the excess, plus a 20 percent excise tax on the executive (4999)", "Mitigated with cutbacks, best-after-tax provisions, or gross-ups (now disfavored)", "Disclosed in the proxy and a flashpoint in say-on-golden-parachute votes"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Golden parachutes are enhanced pay arrangements that reward senior executives if the company undergoes a change of control - accelerated equity vesting, cash severance, and continued benefits. A key design point is the trigger: a single-trigger parachute pays out simply on the deal closing, whereas a double-trigger, which investors prefer, also requires the executive to lose their job afterwards. What really shapes the structuring is the US tax regime in Sections 280G and 4999. If total change-of-control payments to a covered executive reach three times their base amount - roughly average pay over the prior five years - the amount above one times base becomes an excess parachute payment. The penalty is harsh on both sides: the company loses its deduction on that excess, and the executive pays a 20 percent excise tax on top of normal income tax. To manage it, deals use cutbacks that cap payments just under the threshold, best-after-tax clauses, or full gross-ups, though gross-ups are now heavily disfavored. These packages are disclosed in the proxy and are a regular flashpoint in the advisory say-on-golden-parachute vote.$x$),
(1696, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$HSR Filing Basics$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'US', $x$At a basic level, what is the HSR filing and the waiting period, and why does it matter for the timing of a US deal?$x$, $x$["HSR = Hart-Scott-Rodino premerger notification", "Both parties file with FTC and DOJ above size thresholds", "Standard 30-day initial waiting period (15 for cash tenders)", "Cannot close until waiting period expires or is terminated", "One agency reviews, can request more time", "Affects sign-to-close timeline and certainty"]$x$::jsonb, $x$HSR stands for Hart-Scott-Rodino, and it is the US premerger notification regime. Basically, if a deal is large enough to cross the size thresholds, both the buyer and the seller have to file a notification with the FTC and the DOJ before they can close, and then sit through a waiting period. The standard initial waiting period is 30 days, or 15 days for an all-cash tender offer. During that window the parties legally cannot complete the transaction. The agencies divide up who reviews a given deal, and the reviewing agency uses that time to decide whether it has competition concerns. If it does, it can extend the clock, but if it clears the deal or lets the period lapse, you are free to close. For a banker the key point is timing and certainty. HSR is why even a clean deal usually needs at least a month between signing and closing, and it is the first regulatory gate you flag in any process today, since reviews have generally gotten longer and tougher.$x$),
(1697, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Second Request Mechanics$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Walk me through what a second request is, what it does to deal timing, and how you would advise a client to think about it before signing.$x$, $x$["Second request = formal demand for documents and data", "Extends waiting period until substantial compliance plus 30 days", "Signals agency has real concerns, in-depth review", "Hugely burdensome, can add many months and large cost", "Burden is asymmetric, often weighs on antitrust risk allocation", "Drives reverse termination fees and outside date negotiation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A second request is the FTC or DOJ formally demanding a large volume of documents, data, and information after the initial HSR review, and it only happens when the agency thinks the deal might be anticompetitive. Mechanically it stops the clock. Once issued, the waiting period does not end until the parties substantially comply and then a further period, usually 30 days, runs after that. The practical effect is enormous, because substantial compliance can take many months of pulling emails, custodian files, and transaction data, plus economic submissions, so a second request can push a deal out by six months to a year and cost a lot in legal and e-discovery fees. Before signing I would tell a client that the likelihood of a second request drives the whole regulatory package. If overlap is meaningful, you should expect one and negotiate for it, meaning a long outside date, clear efforts obligations, a reverse termination fee sized to the risk, and clarity on who controls the strategy and any divestitures.$x$),
(1698, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Theories Of Harm$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Compare horizontal, vertical, and potential-competition theories of harm. Give a concrete example of each and say which tends to be hardest for the agencies to win on.$x$, $x$["Horizontal = direct competitors, lost rivalry, higher concentration", "Vertical = supplier-customer, input foreclosure or raised rivals costs", "Potential competition = removing a likely future entrant or nascent rival", "Examples for each that fit the sector", "Horizontal easiest, vertical and potential harder to prove", "Tougher agencies now pushing vertical and nascent-competition cases"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Horizontal harm is the classic one. The merging firms compete directly, so combining them removes head-to-head rivalry and raises concentration, which can mean higher prices. Think of two of the few national supermarket chains merging. Vertical harm involves firms at different levels of a supply chain, like a chip maker buying a device maker. The worry is foreclosure, that the combined firm cuts off rivals from a key input or customer, or raises their costs. Potential competition is about the future. The concern is that the target was a likely entrant or a fast-growing nascent rival that would have disciplined the incumbent, so buying it removes competition that has not fully arrived yet, which you see in big tech buying startups. Historically horizontal cases are easiest for the agencies to win because the harm is the most direct and measurable. Vertical and potential competition are harder because they rest on predictions about behavior and the future. That said, the current tougher agencies have been deliberately pushing vertical and nascent-competition theories, so you cannot assume those deals sail through anymore.$x$),
(1699, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Structural Vs Behavioral$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$If a deal raises competition concerns, what is the difference between structural and behavioral remedies, and why do the US agencies currently favor one over the other?$x$, $x$["Structural = divestiture of assets or a business", "Behavioral/conduct = ongoing commitments on pricing, access, firewalls", "Structural is clean, one-time, easy to monitor", "Behavioral needs ongoing oversight, prone to evasion", "Agencies currently prefer structural divestitures", "Divestiture buyer must be viable and approved (upfront buyer)"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A structural remedy fixes the competitive problem by changing the assets of the combined firm, almost always a divestiture, where you sell off a plant, a brand, or a whole business line so that competition is preserved. A behavioral or conduct remedy leaves the firm intact but imposes ongoing rules, like commitments to keep supplying rivals on fair terms, to honor pricing caps, or to maintain firewalls between divisions. The big difference is durability and monitoring. A structural remedy is a clean, one-time cut. Once the asset is sold to a strong buyer, the market is fixed and nobody has to police it for years. Behavioral remedies require continuous oversight, they are hard to enforce, and firms can find ways around them. That is exactly why the US agencies currently strongly favor structural divestitures and are skeptical of conduct remedies, especially after some behavioral deals underperformed. As a banker I would also stress that a divestiture only works if there is a credible, approved buyer, and agencies increasingly want that buyer lined up upfront before they bless the deal.$x$),
(1700, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Failing Firm Defense$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$A distressed target argues the deal should be cleared under the failing-firm defense. What must be shown for that to hold, and why are the agencies skeptical of it?$x$, $x$["Firm would fail and exit absent the merger", "Imminent failure, unable to meet obligations", "No reasonable prospect of successful reorganization (e.g., Chapter 11)", "Good-faith efforts to find a less anticompetitive buyer failed", "Assets would otherwise leave the market", "High bar; agencies treat it as a narrow, fact-heavy exception"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The failing-firm defense says a merger that would normally be anticompetitive should still be allowed because the target is going to fail and leave the market anyway, so combining is no worse for competition than the alternative. To rely on it you essentially have to prove three things. First, the firm is facing imminent failure and cannot meet its obligations as they come due. Second, it could not reasonably reorganize itself, for example through Chapter 11, to survive as an independent competitor. And third, the seller made good-faith but unsuccessful efforts to find an alternative buyer who would pose a less severe competitive threat, meaning you genuinely shopped it to less problematic acquirers. The underlying idea is that the assets and the competition they represent are leaving the market regardless. The agencies are skeptical because it is an easy story to tell and a hard one to prove, and accepting it green-lights concentration. So they hold parties to a very high, document-heavy standard and rarely accept it on the company's say-so. In a sale process, that means papering the auction and the financial distress carefully.$x$),
(1701, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$CFIUS National Security$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A foreign strategic is acquiring a US technology company. Separate from antitrust, how does CFIUS review fit in, when is filing effectively mandatory, and how does it shape your deal terms?$x$, $x$["CFIUS reviews national-security risk of foreign control/investment", "Distinct from antitrust; different agency and standard", "Mandatory in some cases (critical tech, sensitive data, TID businesses)", "Outcomes: clearance, mitigation agreement, or block/divestiture", "President can block or unwind; jurisdiction even post-close", "Drives CFIUS condition, long-stop date, risk allocation, mitigation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$CFIUS is the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States, and it reviews whether a foreign person taking control of, or sometimes a non-controlling stake in, a US business creates a national-security risk. It is completely separate from antitrust. The question is not competition, it is whether sensitive technology, infrastructure, or personal data ends up under foreign influence. Filing is voluntary in general but effectively mandatory in certain cases, for example where the target is a TID business involving critical technologies, critical infrastructure, or sensitive personal data and a foreign government holds an interest, or where critical tech with export-control implications is involved. Outcomes are clearance, clearance with a mitigation agreement that limits access or imposes governance conditions, or a recommendation that the President block or unwind the deal, and CFIUS can reach even a closed deal. So I would build in a specific CFIUS closing condition, a long-stop date that accounts for review and any investigation, allocate the risk if mitigation is required, and pre-agree how far the buyer must go to clear.$x$),
(1702, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$EU Control And FSR$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'EMEA', $x$For a large cross-border deal touching Europe, walk me through EU merger control alongside the newer foreign-subsidies regime, and why a buyer backed by state support now faces two separate EU gates.$x$, $x$["EU Merger Regulation: one-stop review by Commission above turnover thresholds", "Phase I and Phase II, SIEC substantive test", "Suspensory: standstill until clearance", "Foreign Subsidies Regulation is separate, targets distortive non-EU subsidies", "FSR notification thresholds based on deal size and foreign financial contributions", "Two parallel clearances, both can delay or block; state-backed bidders most exposed"]$x$::jsonb, $x$There are now two distinct EU gates. The first is classic merger control under the EU Merger Regulation. If the parties cross the EU turnover thresholds, the European Commission reviews on a one-stop basis instead of multiple national regulators. It runs a Phase I review and, if concerns remain, a deeper Phase II, applying the test of whether the deal significantly impedes effective competition, often through dominance. It is suspensory, so you must stand still and cannot close until cleared. The second, newer gate is the Foreign Subsidies Regulation, which is not about competition at all. It targets subsidies from non-EU governments that distort the EU market, like cheap state financing or guarantees, that let a bidder overpay or outcompete unfairly. Above set deal-size and foreign-contribution thresholds you must notify the Commission separately, and it can clear, impose commitments, or prohibit. So a state-backed buyer faces both reviews in parallel, each with its own standstill and power to add remedies or delay. I would scope both early, because the FSR has materially lengthened timelines for state-linked acquirers.$x$),
(1703, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Allocating Regulatory Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Sell-side, you are negotiating the antitrust risk package on a deal with real overlap. Walk me through the spectrum from a plain reasonable-best-efforts covenant to a hell-or-high-water commitment, and how a reverse termination fee fits the bargain.$x$, $x$["Efforts standard spectrum: reasonable/commercially reasonable to best efforts", "Hell-or-high-water = buyer must do whatever it takes, including divestitures/litigation", "Divestiture commitment can be capped (defined assets or revenue limit)", "Litigate-to-close obligation and who controls strategy", "Reverse termination fee compensates seller if deal dies on antitrust", "RTF sizing balances seller protection vs buyer deterrence; trade-off with efforts level"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Think of it as a dial on how hard the buyer must push to clear. At the weak end is a reasonable or commercially reasonable best-efforts covenant, where the buyer tries but is not forced to take painful steps. In the middle you negotiate a specific divestiture commitment, where the buyer agrees to sell assets if required but caps it, say up to a defined business or a revenue threshold, so the obligation is bounded. At the strong end is hell-or-high-water, where the buyer must do whatever it takes to close, including divesting whatever the agencies demand and even litigating the regulators to a final order. As the seller I want that dial as far toward hell-or-high-water as I can get, plus a litigate-to-close obligation and control of strategy. The reverse termination fee is the backstop, paid to me if the deal still dies on antitrust. The two are linked. If I cannot get a full hell-or-high-water covenant, I push for a larger reverse termination fee so the buyer is motivated and I am compensated for the risk I accept. In today's tougher environment both pieces are heavily contested.$x$),
(1704, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Gun-Jumping Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Between signing and clearance, the buyer wants to coordinate pricing and integrate sales teams with the target. Explain gun-jumping, why this is dangerous, and how you would structure the interim period to stay safe.$x$, $x$["Gun-jumping = acting as merged before clearance / closing", "Two flavors: premature combination of control and unlawful coordination of competitors", "Risks: fines, standstill violations, antitrust liability between independents", "Parties must operate as separate competitors until close", "Use clean teams, limited info sharing, no control over day-to-day", "Interim covenants protect value without ceding operational control"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Gun-jumping is acting as if the deal has closed before you are legally allowed to, either before clearance or before the waiting period ends. It comes in two flavors. One is prematurely combining the businesses, where the buyer starts exercising control over how the target is run day to day. The other, and the one your example screams, is unlawful coordination between firms that are still independent competitors, because until you close you remain rivals. Coordinating pricing or merging sales efforts now is essentially the buyer and target colluding, a serious antitrust violation on its own, separate from the merger, that can draw fines. So in the interim I keep the parties operating as separate competitors. Competitively sensitive information, like detailed pricing and customer specifics, flows only through a clean team walled off from day-to-day decisions, and only as needed for integration planning. The merger agreement protects value through ordinary-course and negative interim covenants that restrict big moves, but it must not hand the buyer operational control. Real integration of pricing and sales waits until after we close.$x$),
(1705, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Value Of Control$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$What does it mean that control has value, and why do acquirers pay a control premium over the trading price?$x$, $x$["Control = power to direct strategy, management, cash, and capture synergies", "Public stock price reflects a minority, passive stake along for the ride", "Whole-company buyer gains power a minority holder never has", "Premium is the extra paid above the unaffected price for that control", "Typically in the twenties-to-thirties-percent range, varies widely by deal", "Premium is the slice of expected gains handed to the seller up front"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Control is the ability to direct a company - set strategy, change management, redeploy cash, capture synergies - and a control premium is the extra someone pays above the unaffected share price to get it. The intuition is that a public stock price reflects a minority, passive stake: you own a sliver and ride along with whatever the incumbent board decides. A buyer taking the whole company gets something a minority holder never has, which is the power to actually change how the business is run and to fold it into their own operations. That incremental power has value, so acquirers routinely pay a premium, often in the twenties-to-thirties-percent range over the undisturbed price, though it varies a lot by deal. The key nuance for who captures the synergy value is this: the premium is the slice of expected gains the buyer hands to the seller up front. If the buyer pays away the entire present value of control and synergies in the premium, the target shareholders capture all of it and the buyer just breaks even. So the premium is really the negotiation over how the combined pie gets split.$x$),
(1706, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Premium Vs Intrinsic Value$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A board is told the offer is a 20 percent premium to the current share price. Why might that not be the right way to judge whether shareholders are fairly paid?$x$, $x$["Premium to market is only fair if the market priced the company correctly", "If stock is undervalued, headline premium can still be below intrinsic value", "If stock is overvalued, even a slim premium may overpay", "Separate premium-to-market (optics) from price-vs-intrinsic (fairness)", "Benchmark against DCF and standalone comps, not just the screen price", "Cleanest deals clear both bars; risky ones lean on premium to a depressed price"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would push back on the framing, because a premium is measured against the wrong benchmark if the stock is mispriced. A control premium is conventionally quoted over the unaffected trading price, but that price is only a fair reference if the market was valuing the company correctly. If I run a DCF and standalone comps and conclude the shares are worth, say, fifty when they are trading at forty, then a bid of forty-eight looks like a healthy twenty percent premium but is actually below my intrinsic value - the buyer is getting the company cheap and the headline premium is flattering. The reverse is just as important: if the stock is frothy and trading above intrinsic value, even a slim premium can be a rich price to pay. So as the target adviser I separate two questions - what is the premium to market, which drives optics and the board's defensibility, versus what is the price relative to standalone intrinsic value, which tells me whether shareholders are actually being fairly compensated. The cleanest deals clear both bars; the dangerous ones rely on a large premium to a depressed price to look generous.$x$),
(1707, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Winner's Curse$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is the winner's curse in M&A, and how would you sanity-check whether a 30 percent premium is justified by synergies?$x$, $x$["Auction winner is often the bidder who most overestimated the asset", "Competitive bidding pushes price past defensible standalone value", "Net synergy PV must cover the premium for the deal to be value-neutral", "5B equity x 30% = 1.5B premium that after-tax synergy PV must at least match", "Capitalize realistic run-rate synergies after tax and net of costs to achieve", "Back out implied synergies from price, do not reverse-engineer a wish list"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The winners curse is the idea that in a competitive auction the party who wins is often the one who most overestimated the asset - by definition you win by being willing to pay more than everyone else, which is a warning sign you may have been too optimistic. In M&A it shows up when several bidders chase one target and the price gets bid up past any defensible standalone value, so the synergies have to do all the work to justify the number. Here is the arithmetic I would run. Suppose the target trades at a five billion equity value and the buyer pays a thirty percent premium, so one and a half billion of premium. To make that deal value-neutral, the present value of net synergies has to at least equal that one and a half billion. The comparison has to be apples to apples: if realistic run-rate cost synergies are, say, two hundred million, I tax-effect them, net the costs to achieve, and capitalize that stream into a present value before holding it up against the premium. The discipline is to back out the synergies implied by the price and ask whether they are credible, rather than starting from a synergy wish list and reverse-engineering a justification.$x$),
(1708, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Synergy Credibility And Dis-Synergies$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How do you assess whether a synergy number in a model is credible, and what are dis-synergies?$x$, $x$["Cost synergies more credible: within company control, traceable, usually realized", "Haircut and phase even cost synergies, net of costs to achieve", "Revenue synergies depend on customers, take longer, miss often - discount or upside", "Dis-synergies: lost dual-sourcing revenue, attrition, distraction during integration", "Honest figure = gross synergies less costs to achieve less dis-synergies, then PV", "Reliance on full-credit day-one revenue synergies signals an overpriced deal"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I trust cost synergies far more than revenue synergies, and I always net off the dis-synergies that management conveniently forgets. Cost synergies - closing duplicate facilities, consolidating overhead, procurement scale - are largely within the combined company's control and show up on a line you can point to, so I give them real weight while still haircutting them and phasing them over a couple of years with the costs to achieve. Revenue synergies - cross-selling, distribution, pricing power - depend on customers behaving as hoped, take longer, and miss far more often, so I discount them heavily or treat them as upside rather than underwriting the price on them. The piece juniors miss is dis-synergies. Mergers leak value too: customers who deliberately dual-source walk when two suppliers become one, key people leave during integration, and revenue can dip. So the honest figure is gross synergies, minus costs to achieve, minus dis-synergies, then phased and present-valued. If the deal only works on full-credit, day-one revenue synergies, that is a red flag the price is too high.$x$),
(1709, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Merger Of Equals$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$What is a merger of equals, and why do the social issues often matter more than the financial terms?$x$, $x$["Stock-for-stock at or near market, little or no premium, neither side clearly the buyer", "Value comes from synergies and re-rating, not a cash takeout", "Social issues: CEO, board seat split, HQ, brand, name, senior team", "Exchange ratio sets each side's pre-agreed ownership slice by contribution", "No premium means target holders must believe the synergy and execution story", "Risk it quietly becomes a takeover if one side dominates board and management"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A merger of equals is a combination structured so neither side is clearly the acquirer - typically a stock-for-stock deal at or near market, with little or no premium, where the value for shareholders comes from synergies and the re-rating of the combined company rather than a cash takeout. Because nobody is being bought, the hard part is rarely the financial terms; it is the social issues. Who becomes CEO, and is there a handover timeline. How are the board seats split between the two sides. Where is the headquarters, whose brand survives, what is the new name, and how is the senior team divided. These governance and ego questions sink more mergers of equals than valuation does. The exchange ratio is set so each side owns a pre-agreed slice of the combined entity - say fifty-five forty-five - reflecting relative contribution. The risk is that a no-premium deal gives target holders no immediate cash gain, so they must believe in the synergy story and execution, and these deals can quietly become a takeover in disguise if one side ends up dominating the combined board and management.$x$),
(1710, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Revlon Sale Process$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$You are advising a target board that has decided to sell the company for cash. At a high level, how do Revlon-type duties shape how you run the process?$x$, $x$["Once control is in play, duty shifts to best price reasonably available now", "Run a defensible process: wide-enough outreach or justified targeted approach", "Keep the board informed and engaged, document who was contacted and why", "Deal-protection terms within market norms so they encourage but do not foreclose better bids", "Preserve a fiduciary out to accept a superior proposal", "No mandatory auction, but must reasonably pursue best value with a clear record"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Once a board decides to sell the company for cash or otherwise put control in play, its duty shifts - in Delaware terms, under Revlon - from preserving the long-term enterprise to getting the best price reasonably available for shareholders right now. Practically, as adviser I am helping the board run a defensible process, not just land a deal. That means casting a wide enough net - a real auction or a well-justified targeted outreach - documenting why we contacted who we contacted, and showing the directors were actively informed and engaged rather than rubber-stamping. I would keep deal-protection terms like the break fee, no-shop, and matching rights within market norms so they encourage a deal without foreclosing a better one, and I would preserve a fiduciary out so the board can still accept a superior proposal. Revlon does not require an auction in every case, and price is not the only factor, but the board must reasonably pursue the best value and create a clear record of having done so, because a sale of control is exactly where courts scrutinize the process most closely.$x$),
(1711, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Critiquing Strategic Rationale$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A slow-growth industrial wants to buy a fast-growing software company and calls it a digital transformation. How would you pressure-test that strategic rationale?$x$, $x$["Distinguish a real synergy story from buying growth = diversification", "Shareholders could buy the target themselves without a control premium", "Probe where synergies actually come from with different customers and cost structures", "Multiple math: low-multiple buyer paying high-multiple price must overcome dilution by execution", "Integration and culture risk drives attrition of the talent you bought", "Separate coherent fit from expensive empire-building wearing a transformation label"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would stress-test the logic before I touch the model, because a clean spreadsheet can dress up a weak strategy. Take a slow-growth industrial buying a fast-growing software company and calling it a digital transformation. First I ask whether the rationale is really a synergy story or just diversification - buying growth you cannot generate organically often destroys value because shareholders could have bought that target themselves without paying a control premium. Second, where do the synergies actually come from. Two businesses with different customers, sales motions, and cost structures may have very little genuine overlap to consolidate, so the cost synergies are thin and the revenue cross-sell is speculative. Third, I look at the multiple math: a low-multiple buyer paying a high-multiple price has to overcome dilution purely through execution. Fourth, integration and culture risk - bolting a software team onto an industrial parent frequently triggers attrition of exactly the talent you bought. My job is to separate a coherent strategic fit from an expensive empire-building exercise wearing a transformation label.$x$),
(1712, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Collar Negotiation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$In a stock deal, what is a collar, and what are the trade-offs between a fixed exchange ratio, a fixed value, and a collared structure?$x$, $x$["Fixed exchange ratio: fixed shares per target share, target bears price risk - buyer-friendly", "Fixed value: fixed dollars, flexes share count, buyer bears dilution risk - target-friendly", "Collar limits how far the payout moves within a price band", "Fixed-value collar holds value in band, floats outside; fixed-ratio collar caps value at edges", "Negotiation is about who absorbs share-price volatility between signing and close", "Often paired with a walk-away right if the price breaches the band badly"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A collar is a mechanism in a stock deal that limits how much the target shareholders payout can move as the buyer share price swings between signing and close. Start with the two pure structures. A fixed exchange ratio fixes the number of buyer shares per target share, so the target bears all the price risk - if the buyer stock falls, the deal value falls with it - which the buyer likes. A fixed value deal fixes the dollar value and flexes the share count, so the buyer bears dilution risk if its stock drops, which the target prefers. A collar splits the difference. A fixed-value collar holds the dollar value constant within a price band and only lets it float once the price moves outside the band; a fixed-ratio collar holds the ratio constant in the middle and caps or floors the value at the edges. Negotiating it is about who eats volatility - the target wants downside protection on value, the buyer wants protection against issuing too many shares. You often pair a collar with a walk-away right, so if the price breaches the band badly a side can renegotiate or terminate rather than be forced into a deal that no longer makes sense.$x$),
(1713, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Hostile Bidder Tactics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A client wants to acquire a company whose board has rejected a friendly approach. How would you advise them on going hostile, and which tactics actually work against a defended target?$x$, $x$["Escalate: bear hug letter first to pressure the board via shareholder awareness", "Two avenues if refused: tender offer to shareholders and proxy contest", "Tender offer alone fails against a poison pill plus staggered board", "Proxy fight is the lever: elect a slate that redeems the pill", "Classified board can stretch this to two annual election cycles", "Consider a toehold for leverage, mind disclosure thresholds, sell the premium narrative"]$x$::jsonb, $x$If a friendly approach has been rebuffed, I would walk a would-be hostile bidder up an escalating ladder rather than going straight to a tender offer. Step one is the bear hug - a private, then if needed public, letter to the board with a specific, attractive price, designed to pressure directors by making shareholders aware of a credible premium they would have to justify rejecting. If the board still refuses, the two real avenues are a tender offer straight to shareholders and a proxy contest, and the key point is which one works. Against a company with a poison pill and a staggered board, a tender offer alone fails, because the pill blocks accumulation and you cannot redeem it without controlling the board. So the proxy fight becomes the lever - you run a slate to replace directors, who then pull the pill, and with a classified board that often takes two annual cycles. I would also weigh building a toehold stake early for leverage, mind the disclosure thresholds when crossing them, and frame the campaign around the premium and a clear value narrative to win over institutions and the proxy advisers.$x$) on conflict do nothing;
